---
Interactive AI chat with session persistence and tool access.

Examples:
  # Interactive chat session
  cru chat

  # One-shot query
  cru chat "Explain the architecture"

  # Resume previous session
  cru chat --resume chat-20250102-1430-a1b2

  # Use specific agent
  cru chat --agent claude-code

  # Plan mode (read-only)
  cru chat --plan

Usage: chat [OPTIONS] [QUERY]

Arguments:
  [QUERY]
          Optional one-shot query (if omitted, starts interactive mode)

Options:
  -a, --agent <AGENT>
          Preferred ACP agent to use (claude-code, gemini-cli, codex, or custom profile)

  -r, --resume <RESUME>
          Resume a previous session by ID (format: chat-YYYYMMDD-HHMM-xxxx)

  -e, --env <KEY=VALUE>
          Environment variables to pass to the ACP agent (can be repeated) Format: KEY=VALUE Example: --env ANTHROPIC_BASE_URL=http://localhost:4000

      --set <KEY[=VALUE]>
          Session configuration overrides in vim-style format (can be repeated) Same syntax as TUI :set — examples: --set model=llama3 --set temperature=0.5 Use --set key for boolean flags (e.g. --set perm.autoconfirm_session)

      --provider <PROVIDER>
          LLM provider to use (from config [llm.providers])

      --max-context <MAX_CONTEXT>
          Maximum context window tokens for internal agent (default: 16384)
          
          [default: 16384]

      --no-context
          Skip context enrichment (faster, but agent has no knowledge base access)

      --context-size <CONTEXT_SIZE>
          Number of context results to include (default: 5)
          
          [default: 5]

      --plan
          Start in plan mode (read-only) instead of normal mode (full access) Can be toggled during session with /plan and /normal commands

      --record <RECORD>
          Record TUI session to a JSONL file for later replay

      --replay <REPLAY>
          Replay a previously recorded JSONL session

      --replay-speed <REPLAY_SPEED>
          Playback speed multiplier for replay (default: 1.0)
          
          [default: 1.0]

      --replay-auto-exit [<DELAY_MS>]
          Auto-exit after replay completes. Optional value is delay in milliseconds (default: 2000)

  -h, --help
          Print help (see a summary with '-h')
